Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 51st Weekly Dose of Optimism.
I texted Packy yesterday morning =E2=80=9Cdamn, pretty slow week for the op=
timists huh?=E2=80=9D and he replied with like 7 different links to stories=
 that could all feasibly be included in this weekly roundup.
Turns out we humans don=E2=80=99t take weeks off from accomplishing big thi=
ngs.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Composer [ https://link.sbstck=
=2Ecom/redirect/976389d6-789d-49c6-a8e=
6-5fcdb6a6c295?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
You know Composer [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/976389d6-789d-49c6-a8e=
6-5fcdb6a6c295?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] and we love Composer [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/976389d6-7=
89d-49c6-a8e6-5fcdb6a6c295?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. But if we=E2=80=99re being honest, for a while the pr=
oduct was really only accessible for pretty sophisticated traders. Setting =
up Symphonies could be complicated and frankly I (Dan) had a hard time navi=
gating the product. But Composer=E2=80=99s new Create with AI tool makes so=
phisticated Symphony building incredibly easy.
I built a Symphony using the following prompt:=20
=E2=80=9CBuild me a strategy that takes advantage of increased demand for G=
PUs, interest rates rising one more time in 6-12 months and staying steady =
or going down thereafter. Also go long undervalued tech stocks. Add in some=
 Meta. Make slightly less risky.=E2=80=9D=20
And Voila, I had a portfolio of assets allocated to satisfy my strategy. It=
=E2=80=99s doing pretty well, too.
Composer AI is the best way to go from idea to execution. Beyond straight u=
p using ChatGPT, this is the most practical use of AI in any product I use =
on a regular basis.
(1) Inflation Eased to 3% in June, Slowest Pace in More Than Two Years [ ht=
tps://link.sbstck.com/redirect/f31ec94e-fbd7-4cb8-8725-c23918e28b39?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Gwynn Guilford [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/069f2a34-c255-43ad-bdc8-e=
532c140418d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for WSJ
Inflation cooled last month to its slowest pace in more than two years, giv=
ing Americans relief from a painful period of rising prices [ https://link.=
sbstck.com/redirect/75214d5a-4b8d-4e87-8a86-44cec16f2e05?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and boosting the chances=
 that the Federal Reserve will stop raising interest rates after an expecte=
d increase this month.
We=E2=80=99ve stayed away from too much commentary on the macro over the pa=
st couple of years, mainly because we know enough to know that we don=E2=80=
=99t know much about the macroeconomy let alone how to predict it. With tha=
t said, it looks like the J-Pow led Federal Reserve has done a pretty solid=
 job of reigning in inflation without destroying the overall economy. Infla=
tion has slowed to its slowest pace in more than two years, unemployment is=
 low, and the S&P 500 has performed strongly so far in 2023.
We are not saying we=E2=80=99re back. That=E2=80=99s about the most surefir=
e to assure that we are indeed not back. But what we can say, with some deg=
ree of certainty, is that things seem to be moving in the direct direction =
and that, at least for now, what could have been a pretty messy economic si=
tuation looks to have been pretty solidly managed.
A strong economy. Steadying interest rates. Reshoring manufacturing. Hotbed=
 of AI.
(2) Proof You Can Do Hard Things [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/48aac9f=
3-4ce1-46e8-83b8-68aa84eb105f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
By Nat Eliason [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/2220e209-01c8-4c06-b690-0=
dccb28fbdcd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]
The ability to do hard things is perhaps the most useful ability you can fo=
ster in yourself or your children. And proof that you are someone who can d=
o them is one of the most useful assets you can have on your life resume.
We can do hard things. But should we do hard things? What=E2=80=99s the poi=
nt?
Nat Eliason reflected on this question in his recent essay and came to the =
conclusion that, yes, we should do hard things. Regardless of whatever that=
 hard thing is, doing hard things is a good thing.=20
The harder you push yourself to accomplish something, the more competent yo=
u will see yourself to be, and the more competent you you believe yourself =
to be, the more hard work you will take on, the more hard work you take on =
the less =E2=80=9Chard=E2=80=9D everything else in life will seem to be.
Go out and do something hard this weekend. (Sorry, a bit hardo, I know.)
(3) The Alchemy of Carbon Removal: How Charm Industrial Plans to Run Oil We=
lls in Reverse and Turn Corn Into Steel [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/=
25df58a1-76d7-4c7c-a191-9197818d1c1d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
By Barrett Brooks [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/9299cc05-f3cc-4d95-afc=
5-04406594d153?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ]
Enter Peter Reinhardt, the technologist and startup founder who sold his la=
st company for $3.2B and decided to tackle climate change for his next act.=
 After teaming up with his co-founders, Shaun and Kelly Kinetic, they decid=
ed to tackle climate change by running oil wells in reverse and decarbonizi=
ng steel. The key? Corn (and other natural waste, or biomass).
Speaking of hard things, Peter Reinhardt is trying to turn biomass into per=
manent carbon storage, in order to advance CO2 removal. We=E2=80=99ve brief=
ly written about his company, Charm Industrial [ https://link.sbstck.com/re=
direct/58580461-96ed-497f-9c00-07b1d36a4b33?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], a few times, mostly due to its conne=
ction to Frontier [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/25075920-50aa-4745-b0d=
c-e10799c0e629?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ] (the Advance Market Commitment from Stripe and others to glavanize=
 the carbon removal industry.)
But this profile from Barrett Brooks goes much deeper on Charm, its approac=
h, and its founder. Reinhardt sold his first business, Segment, to Twilio f=
or  $3.2B in 2020. The deal likely made Reinhardt a few hundred million dol=
lars. And with this newfound wealth (and time), Reinhardt went all-in on so=
lving hard problems. He=E2=80=99s part of a growing class of ZIRP entrepren=
eurs that are investing bits-made wealth into atoms-focused challenges.
(4) Astranis to bring satellite internet to 2 million people in the Philipp=
ines next year [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/8ee30102-a84e-4e96-9169-7=
1c0ff0f5baa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]
Michael Sheetz [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/0e5466e8-9564-46b9-b604-f=
7f1f346bb5a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] for CNBC
=E2=80=9CWe estimate that we will get up to 2 million people connected, hav=
ing access to this broadband internet that they didn=E2=80=99t have before,=
=E2=80=9D Gedmark added.
Astranis is bringing a dedicated satellite to the Philippines, unlocking in=
ternet access for an estimated 2M Philippinos. You likely haven=E2=80=99t h=
eard of Astranis, but the best way to think of it is that it=E2=80=99s Star=
link for the masses. It=E2=80=99s=C2=A0focused on connecting people who pay=
 <$2/month for internet=C2=A0today=C2=A0and might make less in an entire ye=
ar than Starlink charges for their premium satellite dish. Astranis works w=
ith telecoms to deliver connectivity, whereas Starlink is accessible by ind=
ividual consumers like you and me. They serve different parts of the market=
, but at the end of the day both companies make the internet more accessibl=
e.=20
More opportunity for more people, and more people contributing to humanity=
=E2=80=99s giant collective brain.=20
(5) x.ai [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/fa59807e-832c-4637-91b4-722281a=
cd0d1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
The goal of xAI is to understand the true nature of the universe.
Speaking of bringing brains online=E2=80=A6 Packy here. I had a little bit =
of fun with Elon=E2=80=99s Twitter acquisition earlier this week in Praise =
Elon [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/be886af2-3887-4a9c-ba6e-6eff710e065=
c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I d=
on=E2=80=99t think he=E2=80=99s doing a great job there. But I=E2=80=99m al=
so pumped that he=E2=80=99s launching xAI with the goal to =E2=80=9CUnderst=
and the Universe.=E2=80=9D=20
Details are sparse so far, but Chroma=E2=80=99s Anton Troynikov put togethe=
r a short thread [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/b606d6b8-679f-48d2-9ebe=
-b1941fb50ba3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] on what he thinks xAI is up to. The TL;DR is that they=E2=80=99re g=
oing to try to use AI to =E2=80=9Csolve math=E2=80=9D in order to figure ou=
t if the universe is explicable, =E2=80=9Ci.e., is it even possible for hum=
an cognition to model and understand the universe at full fidelity.=E2=80=
=9D=20
That seems useful and wondrous and optimistic. We=E2=80=99re big fans of Da=
vid Deutsch=E2=80=99s Principle of Optimism here: =E2=80=9CAll evil is caus=
ed by insufficient knowledge.=E2=80=9D If Elon and the xAI team is successf=
ul, it will take a big bite out of our insufficient knowledge.=20
Will they succeed? Who knows. But Elon has as good a shot as anyone. In the=
 intro to Tuesday=E2=80=99s piece, I wrote that =E2=80=9CSomeone can be wor=
ld-class at some things and not as good at other things,=E2=80=9D and this =
feels like something he can be world-class at. Assembling an all-star team =
to solve really hard technical challenges is what he does at his best.=20
Whether xAI ultimately understands the universe or not, this is the kind of=
 challenge I=E2=80=99m excited to see well-resourced people address. Now Sa=
m Altman just needs to goad him into working on fusion [ https://link.sbstc=
k.com/redirect/4f47728d-4535-4b8c-a296-86ea9c949ca0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=A6=20
(Bonus) The American System is Working
Packy again. I gotta be honest. I=E2=80=99ve felt disheartened by America=
=E2=80=99s regulatory stance towards innovation for the last little while. =
Gary Gensler=E2=80=99s SEC has been regulating crypto through enforcement i=
n a pretty transparent effort to kill the industry. Lina Khan=E2=80=99s FTC=
 has been going hard after big tech companies and limiting exit options for=
 startups in the process. Both Genlser and Khan seem more motivated by star=
dom than by actually protecting consumers.=20
And they would have gotten away with it, too, if it weren=E2=80=99t for you=
 meddling judges!=20
This past week has been a nice reminder that while America has its issues, =
the system is actually pretty robust against bad actors.=20
On Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Jacqueline Scott Corley ruled against the=
 FTC in its attempt to block Microsoft=E2=80=99s acquisition of Activision.=
 Ben Thompson has a good breakdown here [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/=
01331568-f4ba-4788-bdcb-1af34ba1b7ab?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], which he concluded with: =E2=80=9CIt is, I =
would grant, problematic to have a regulator that is too permissive; it=E2=
=80=99s worse, though, to have one that is so ideological that every opinio=
n against it is embarrassing in the totality of its dismissiveness.=E2=80=
=9D=20
The Wall Street Journal Editorial Board [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/=
6d6504c1-41bc-466e-b0ff-6283af17a17f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] was even more blunt about Khan: =E2=80=9CYet=
 this is Ms. Khan=E2=80=99s method: Sue first based on dubious or long-repu=
diated antitrust legal theories, then scramble to find evidence to support =
the agency=E2=80=99s claims. A CEO with her record of failure would be out =
of a job.=E2=80=9D
If that approach sounds familiar, it=E2=80=99s because it=E2=80=99s similar=
 to the one Gensler has been taking to crypto at the SEC: enforce first, ma=
ke rules later.=20
And in another bit of great news [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/8e2ef8a=
b-4148-4189-848e-57a443f9ded7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for innovation, =E2=80=9CU.S. District Judge Analis=
a Torres agreed with Ripple Labs=E2=80=99 argument that roughly half of its=
 sales of XRP didn=E2=80=99t violate investor-protection laws.=E2=80=9D The=
 XRP tokens Ripple sold directly to institutional investors were securities=
, which Ripple should have registered, and the company faces penalties for =
not doing so. Importantly, however, the XRP tokens Ripple sold through exch=
anges were not securities offerings, implying that cryptocurrencies listed =
on exchanges aren=E2=80=99t necessarily securities, no matter how they were=
 originally sold.=20
I=E2=80=99m not a particularly big fan of Ripple, but I am a fan of the pre=
cedent the case sets for good projects in crypto. There=E2=80=99s a little =
more clarity. Plus, the XRP case =E2=80=94 which a lawyer friend told me co=
uld not have had a worse set of facts for Ripple =E2=80=94 should set the t=
one for upcoming SEC legal battles against crypto, including the big one ag=
ainst Coinbase.=20
Lest we get too excited, the battles are still ongoing. The order in the Ri=
pple case is =E2=80=9Cjust a partial summary judgment from a single distric=
t court judge [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/881161a9-727a-495a-839e-86=
8c2dc42b6a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ].=E2=80=9D The Coinbase case is still to come. Khan will appeal the Mic=
rosoft/Activision decision. The FTC has ongoing investigations of all of th=
e big tech companies, including a fresh one into OpenAI [ https://link.sbst=
ck.com/redirect/8d9e193b-46be-438c-95c6-1650b9bd779e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], and the SEC would like to c=
ontinue to try to sue crypto out of existence. It=E2=80=99s too early for v=
ictory laps. That said, it=E2=80=99s great to see those checks and balances=
 you learned about in 5th Grade Social Studies class in action.=20
Regulation and enforcement are important and healthy. Celsius CEO Alex Mash=
insky was arrested this week [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/69a59aa2-a0=
96-4bf5-b602-a6c0a07594ad?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepK=
bqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and the crypto industry cheered. Real consumer protect=
ion, and real consequences for those who intentionally harm consumers, are =
great things.=20
But abusing power to extrajudicially push through an ideological and celebr=
ity-motivated agenda is not good, and it makes me very happy to see that, f=
or now, it=E2=80=99s also ineffective.=20
Two wannabe regfluencers overreached, and the American legal system slapped=
 their hands. Entrepreneurs can build with a little more confidence in the =
system. God Bless America.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tu=
esday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan + Packy

